# Getting Started with the deSEC Provider

This guide walks through the essential steps for managing DNS with [deSEC](https://desec.io) using Terraform:
registering a domain, retrieving its nameservers and DNSSEC material, and creating DNS records.

## Prerequisites

1. Create a free account at [desec.io](https://desec.io).
2. Generate an API token in the deSEC web interface under **Token Management**.
3. Configure the provider with your token:

```terraform
provider "desec" {
  api_token = var.desec_api_token
}

variable "desec_api_token" {
  type      = string
  sensitive = true
}
```

You can also set the `DESEC_API_TOKEN` environment variable instead of passing the token inline.

## Step 1: Register a Domain

Use the `desec_domain` resource to register a domain with deSEC:

```terraform
resource "desec_domain" "example" {
  name = "example.com"
}
```

After `terraform apply`, the domain is created in deSEC and nameservers are automatically assigned.

-> **Note:** deSEC also supports free subdomains under `dedyn.io` (e.g. `myproject.dedyn.io`).

-> **Tip:** For internationalized domain names (IDN), the provider offers the
[`provider::desec::to_punycode()`](../functions/to_punycode) and
[`provider::desec::from_punycode()`](../functions/from_punycode) functions.
The deSEC API requires Punycode form, so use `to_punycode()` when registering unicode domains:

```terraform
resource "desec_domain" "idn" {
  name = provider::desec::to_punycode("münchen.de")
}
```

## Step 2: Access Nameservers and DNSSEC Material

### Nameservers

Look up the NS records assigned by deSEC using the `desec_rrset` data source. You will need to enter
these at your domain registrar to delegate the domain to deSEC.

```terraform
data "desec_rrset" "nameservers" {
  domain  = desec_domain.example.name
  subname = "@"
  type    = "NS"
}

output "nameservers" {
  description = "Enter these nameservers at your domain registrar."
  value       = data.desec_rrset.nameservers.rdata
}
```

### DNSSEC

deSEC automatically signs your zone with DNSSEC. The signing keys are available on the
`desec_domain` resource via the `keys` attribute. To enable DNSSEC validation, enter the
DS records at your domain registrar:

```terraform
output "dnssec_ds_records" {
  description = "DS records for DNSSEC delegation — enter these at your domain registrar."
  value       = flatten([for key in desec_domain.example.keys : key.ds if key.managed])
}

output "dnssec_dnskeys" {
  description = "DNSKEY public key records for DNSSEC verification."
  value       = [for key in desec_domain.example.keys : key.dnskey if key.managed]
}
```

## Step 3: Create DNS Records

Use the `desec_rrset` resource to create individual DNS record sets. Each resource manages
one RRset (a combination of domain, subname, and type).

```terraform
resource "desec_rrset" "www_a" {
  domain  = desec_domain.example.name
  subname = "www"
  type    = "A"
  ttl     = 3600
  rdata   = ["203.0.113.10"]
}

resource "desec_rrset" "mx" {
  domain  = desec_domain.example.name
  subname = "@"
  type    = "MX"
  ttl     = 3600
  rdata   = ["10 mail.example.com."]
}

resource "desec_rrset" "spf" {
  domain  = desec_domain.example.name
  subname = "@"
  type    = "TXT"
  ttl     = 3600
  rdata   = ["\"v=spf1 mx ~all\""]
}
```

-> **Tip:** Use `@` or `""` for `subname` to create records at the zone apex. The `rdata` field
is a set of strings — multiple values create a multi-value RRset (e.g. round-robin A records).

## Step 4: Bulk Record Management

For domains with many records, the [`desec_records`](../resources/records) resource is a better
fit than individual `desec_rrset` resources. It sends all record changes in a single bulk API
request, which avoids deSEC rate limits that can occur when managing many `desec_rrset` resources
in parallel.

`desec_records` also accepts a BIND-style zone file, making it easy to migrate existing DNS
configurations:

```terraform
resource "desec_records" "bulk" {
  domain    = desec_domain.example.name
  exclusive = true

  zonefile = <<-ZONE
    example.com.      3600 IN A     203.0.113.10
    example.com.      3600 IN AAAA  2001:db8::1
    www.example.com.  3600 IN A     203.0.113.10
    example.com.      3600 IN MX    10 mail.example.com.
    example.com.      3600 IN TXT   "v=spf1 mx ~all"
  ZONE
}
```

Setting `exclusive = true` makes this resource the single source of truth for all records on the
domain — any records not declared here are deleted. This is useful for ensuring no unmanaged records
exist. You can also load the zone file from disk using `file()` or `templatefile()`:

```terraform
resource "desec_records" "bulk" {
  domain    = desec_domain.example.name
  exclusive = true
  zonefile  = file("${path.module}/example.com.zone")
}
```

-> **Note:** `desec_records` can also use structured `rrsets` blocks instead of a zone file.
See the [`desec_records` resource documentation](../resources/records) for details.

